Dynamic Styling

Dynamic styling in React means applying styles based on component state, props, or other runtime conditions. 
This can be done using conditional className values or inline style objects.


1. Dynamic className

function Status({ isOnline }) {
    return (
        <h1 className={isOnline ? "online" : "offline"}>
            User Status
        </h1>
    )
}

.online {
    color: green;
}

.offline {
    color: red;
}


2. Inline Dynamic Styles

function Status({ isOnline }) {
    return (
        <h1
            style={{
                color: isOnline ? "green" : "red"
            }}
        >
            User Status
        </h1>
    )
}


3. Multiple Dynamic Styles

<button
    style={{
        backgroundColor: isActive ? "blue" : "gray",
        color: "white",
        border: isActive
            ? "2px solid blue"
            : "2px solid gray"
    }}
>
    Submit
</button>


4. Using Variables

const buttonStyle = {
    backgroundColor: isActive ? "blue" : "gray",
    color: "white"
}

return (
    <button style={buttonStyle}>
        Submit
    </button>
)


5. Dynamic Styles from State

const [isFavorite, setIsFavorite] = useState(false)

return (
    <button
        style={{
            color: isFavorite ? "gold" : "black"
        }}
        onClick={() => setIsFavorite(prev => !prev)}
    >
        ★
    </button>
)


6. Conditional Rendering + Styling

<div
    className={
        count > 0
            ? "has-items"
            : "empty"
    }
>
    Cart
</div>


Q: Why does React use style={{}}?

Because the style prop expects a JavaScript object.

style={{
    color: "red",
    backgroundColor: "blue"
}}

Outer {} enters JavaScript mode, inner {} creates the object.


Q: Why is it backgroundColor and not background-color?

React style objects use JavaScript property names, which follow camelCase.


Q: Dynamic className vs inline styles?

className is preferred for larger, reusable styles.
Inline styles are useful for small dynamic values such as colors, widths, or transforms.
